      <h3 style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 19px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Fulshaw Park - the prestige estate</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Fulshaw Park is Wilmslow's most sought-after residential address, with large detached homes on private roads behind mature hedgerows. Properties here rarely come to market - when they do, competition is intense, with asking prices from £1.2 million to above £1.55 million (Rightmove, 2025). The estate sits south of the town centre with walking access to both The Carrs Park and Wilmslow station.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The housing stock is predominantly 1920s-1950s individually designed detached homes on plots of 0.25 to 0.5 acres, many with double garages and south-facing gardens. Several properties have been extended or rebuilt, but the estate's private road covenants restrict subdivision and maintain the low-density character. Fulshaw Park falls within the Gorsey Bank Primary catchment - a further pricing factor given that school's Outstanding Ofsted rating (2023).</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 19px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Harden Park - the executive estate</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Harden Park is Wilmslow's principal executive estate, with 1960s-1970s detached homes on generous plots averaging above £900,000 (Rightmove, 2025). The estate occupies the northeast corner of the town, between Handforth and the A34, and suits families who want four-to-five-bedroom homes with large gardens at a lower entry point than Fulshaw Park while remaining within the Wilmslow High School catchment.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The estate is quieter than areas closer to the town centre but sits further from the station - a 15-to-20-minute walk or a short drive. Buyers choosing Harden Park typically drive to the station or to Handforth Dean retail park rather than relying on the walkable town centre.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 19px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Lacey Green - the family heartland</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Lacey Green is Wilmslow's most established family neighbourhood, centred on Lacey Green Primary Academy (Good, Ofsted 2023) and a cluster of 1950s-1970s semi-detached and detached homes. At £500,000 average, it represents the mid-market tier - below the premium estates but above the town centre flat market.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The area has a settled, low-turnover character. Properties circulate within school-age family networks, meaning the best stock often sells before reaching open-market listing. Buyers targeting Lacey Green should register with local estate agents early and monitor pre-market listings. The neighbourhood borders Lindow to the west, giving residents walking access to Lindow Common without the higher prices of the Lindow fringe.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 19px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Dean Row - the quieter south</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Dean Row is Wilmslow's quietest residential area, extending south towards the rural fringe and the village of Handforth. At £450,000 average, it offers family-sized homes with more garden space than the town centre at roughly 23% below the Wilmslow-wide average. The housing stock mixes 1970s estates with scattered older cottages along Dean Row Road.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Dean Row is further from the station (a 20-to-25-minute walk) and has fewer local amenities, but the trade-off is space and quiet. St Chad's Church and the surrounding green space give the area a semi-rural feel despite its Wilmslow postcode. Buyers who prioritise garden size and tranquillity over walkability find Dean Row the best value within the SK9 postcode area.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 19px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Lindow - green fringe living</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Lindow sits on Wilmslow's western edge adjacent to Lindow Common, a Site of Special Scientific Interest with lowland heath and birch woodland. The area attracts buyers who want countryside access within a 10-minute walk of the town centre. Housing stock is mixed - 1930s semis alongside more recent detached homes averaging £550,000 (Rightmove, 2025).</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Lindow Community Primary School (Good, Ofsted) serves the neighbourhood, and the station is a 15-minute walk via Hawthorn Lane. Lindow Common is also the site of the Lindow Man discovery - an Iron Age bog body preserved for 2,000 years, now exhibited in the British Museum.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 19px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Wilmslow Park - period homes near The Carrs</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Wilmslow Park sits between the town centre and The Carrs parkland, offering a mix of Victorian terraces, Edwardian semis, and interwar detached homes. At £475,000 average, the area appeals to buyers who value period character and walking proximity to both the park and the high street. The River Bollin runs along the southern boundary, and morning walks through The Carrs to the station take roughly 12 minutes on foot.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 19px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">Wilmslow Town Centre - convenience at lower cost</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Central Wilmslow combines the most walkable convenience in SK9 - station, restaurants, and shops within five minutes - with the lowest entry prices at around £350,000 average, primarily apartments and smaller terraced properties. The trade-off is evening noise from the high street and limited garden space. For first-time buyers and downsizers, the town centre provides the Wilmslow commute and amenity at roughly 60% of the suburb average.</p>
